postcontent:
This gun is in excellent condition.  I used this gun as my primary concealed carry gun for about two years.  I shot around 1,000 rounds through this gun and have not had one feed/eject problem ever.  I read about problems with some of these guns.  So after I bought it, I took it apart and cleaned it very thoroughly and mirror-polished the feed ramp before I ever shot this gun. I added a Crimson Trace trigger guard mount laser (LG-447).  I also like that this gun has a round-in-the chamber indicator, trigger safety, and a thumb safety.  Always carry it "cocked and locked" (7+1). It has been a great carry gun.

title: For Sale:  Hungarian G98/40 Mauser All Matching Unissued Mint
postcontent:
The Hungarian-made G98/40 is not a Mauser and shares little with the G98 but is instead patterned after the Hungarian 35M. These rifles were contracted as a war-expedient to exploit the existing Hungarian 35M tooling. These rifles were primarily issued to Luftwaffe.
G98/40 infantry rifles are among the rarest Third Reich infantry rifles a collector is likely to encounter and should be recognized and purchased at any opportunity. Very few examples survived the war.
This example is an all-matching "jhv" coded 1943 in excellent condition with clear, unaltered Waffenamts. The wood has a few dents and dings but no major damage or repairs.
